se your confidence as a trainer - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-gtJxSR jkHSry pf-23_"/></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-5fef" data-category="Generic Content" data-name="Matcha" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-dBFCZX khzvmY pf-24_"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-gvPcJq dRaLso"><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-25_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:0px;--s-sm:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-26_"><p class="sc-eONOlN cfGtgs pf-27_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cHMHbD bwTmDt pf-29_">Our train-the-trainer courses are suited to training managers who wish to learn how to develop organisational training programmes which focus on the implementation of training policies as well as improving internal staff competency levels. Alternatively, a <i><a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/pages/train-the-trainer-courses-and-qualifications" target="_blank"><span style="color: rgb(0, 102, 204);">train-the-trainer course</span></a></i> can provide the opportunity to gain the necessary tools and qualifications to pursue a career as an external trainer.
<br><br>Being a subject matter expert is just one aspect of becoming an effective trainer. You must be able to deliver your knowledge effectively to your learners. Even trainers who are excellent communicators can sometimes experience nervousness. In our previous <a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/blogs/education-and-training/what-are-the-traits-of-a-good-trainer" target="_blank"><i>blog post</i></a>, we discussed the qualities of a good trainer. This article will highlight some important factors that can help trainers boost their confidence.
</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-fUklNj thmnJ pf-30_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cHMHbD bwTmDt pf-32_">Practice and rehearsal</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Practice_and_rehearsal.png?v=1690886400" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Practice_and_rehearsal.png?v=1690886400 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Practice_and_rehearsal_500x.png?v=1690886400 320w" width="2048" height="1166" alt="Practice and rehearsal - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Practice and rehearsal - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-gtJxSR jkHSry pf-33_"/><p class="sc-eONOlN cfGtgs pf-34_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cHMHbD bwTmDt pf-36_">Engaging in practice and rehearsal of training sessions, particularly for new or complex content, can greatly enhance an individual's confidence as a trainer. Trainers can better prepare themselves by conducting run-throughs of presentations, anticipating potential questions, and refining their delivery. This preparation helps alleviate anxiety and enables trainers to establish a consistent and reliable delivery style. Ultimately, practising and rehearsing training sessions are valuable tools for trainers to build confidence and refine their skills.
</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-fUklNj thmnJ pf-37_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cHMHbD bwTmDt pf-39_">Positive self-talk and visualisation</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Positive_self-talk_and_visualisation.png?v=1690886400" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Positive_self-talk_and_visualisation.png?v=1690886400 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Positive_self-talk_and_visualisation_500x.png?v=1690886400 320w" width="2048" height="1367" alt="Positive self-talk and visualisation - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Positive self-talk and visualisation - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-gtJxSR jkHSry pf-40_"/><p class="sc-eONOlN cfGtgs pf-41_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cHMHbD bwTmDt pf-43_">Promoting positive self-talk and utilising visualisation techniques can significantly influence enhancing confidence. Trainers have the ability to reinforce their competence through affirmations, mentally visualise successful training sessions, and concentrate on their strengths and previous accomplishments. By cultivating this mindset, trainers foster self-belief and greater confidence in their abilities. These practices serve as powerful tools to bolster confidence levels and contribute to the overall effectiveness of trainers.

</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-fUklNj thmnJ pf-44_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cHMHbD bwTmDt pf-46_">Embrace the acceptance of not having every answer </span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Embrace_the_acceptance_of_not_having_every_answer.png?v=1690886400" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Embrace_the_acceptance_of_not_having_every_answer.png?v=1690886400 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Embrace_the_acceptance_of_not_having_every_answer_500x.png?v=1690886400 320w" width="2048" height="1366" alt="Embrace the acceptance of not having every answer - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Embrace the acceptance of not having every answer - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-gtJxSR jkHSry pf-47_"/><p class="sc-eONOlN cfGtgs pf-48_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cHMHbD bwTmDt pf-50_">In situations where you find yourself put on the spot, you may find you’re not able to recall an answer immediately. In such instances, a valuable technique is to redirect the question back to the group and foster a discussion. By posing the question, "What do you think the answer might be?" trainers empower participants to contribute their own knowledge and insights. This approach cultivates an interactive and collaborative learning environment where everyone is involved in the process of exploring and discovering solutions together.</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-fUklNj thmnJ pf-51_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cHMHbD bwTmDt pf-53_">Feedback and reflection</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Feedback_and_reflection.png?v=1690886400" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Feedback_and_reflection.png?v=1690886400 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Feedback_and_reflection_500x.png?v=1690886400 320w" width="2048" height="1366" alt="Feedback and reflection - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Feedback and reflection - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-gtJxSR jkHSry pf-54_"/><p class="sc-eONOlN cfGtgs pf-55_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cHMHbD bwTmDt pf-57_">Engaging in a feedback loop with participants and colleagues can yield valuable insights that trainers can leverage to enhance their skills. Constructive feedback plays a pivotal role in facilitating growth and improvement. Additionally, trainers should actively reflect on their training sessions, identifying both their strengths and areas that warrant further development. This introspection contributes to their overall confidence and allows trainers to refine their approach over time. By embracing feedback and engaging in self-reflection, trainers can continuously elevate their capabilities and deliver more impactful training experiences.
